 Migration follows the same pattern as 20260218150242_create_password_resets_table.ts.

 ---
 Redis Key Convention

 rt:{sha256(rawRefreshTokenJWT)}  →  "{dbRecordId}"   TTL = token remaining seconds

 Storing the DB record id as the value lets us skip a lookup when rotating tokens.
 The raw JWT is never stored — only its hash (same principle as OTP hashing).

 ---
 Token Lifecycle

 On login / register (existing methods get extended)

 1. Create JWT with createRefreshToken(payload)
 2. Hash raw JWT with hashOTP (reuse existing SHA-256 helper)
 3. Store hash in refresh_tokens table → get back the row id
 4. Decode JWT with decodeJwt (already imported) to get exp
 5. cacheSet('rt:{hash}', String(id), exp - now) in Redis

 POST /auth/refresh

 1. Read refresh_token cookie — if missing throw InvalidRefreshToken
 2. Hash the raw token
 3. cacheGet('rt:{hash}') — Redis hit → get DB record id (no DB call)
 4. Redis miss → findRefreshTokenByHash(hash) from DB
 5. If still not found → throw InvalidRefreshToken
 6. verifyRefreshToken(rawToken) — validates signature + expiry via jose
 7. Rotate: cacheDel + revokeRefreshToken(id) for old token
 8. Create new refresh token JWT, hash it, persist to DB + Redis
 9. Create new access token from JWT payload
 10. setAuthCookies with both new tokens, respond 200

 POST /auth/logout

 1. Read refresh_token cookie — if missing, just clear cookies + respond 200
 2. Hash the raw token
 3. cacheDel('rt:{hash}') — always delete from Redis even if it's a miss
 4. revokeRefreshToken by hash in DB (single UPDATE … WHERE token_hash = ?)
 5. Clear both cookies, respond 200

